g.title: Folded Corner.69
g.desc: The Decorator pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle b...

g.text: The Decorator pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by enhancing the functionality of an existing object without changing it. The pattern accomplishes this by preferring composition over inheritance. This enhances the stability, readability, reusability and testability of the code. All aspects are compared against an implementation where inheritance (sub-classing) is used to extend the behavior of our system. Stability, because the chance of breaking code unrelated to the change becomes smaller. Inheritance is a ‘tighter’ relation as composition. Distributing the extensions across different objects (=Decorators) and applying them via composition minimizes the impact of change. The goal remains to minimize change, but in case it is required, composition is preferred. Reusability, because different objects (=Components) can reuse the same extensions (=Decorator). In contrast, using inheritance might result in duplication in case a lot of small variations are required across different inheritance branches. Testability, because each Decorator can be tested in isolation. In contrast, inheritance has a tight coupling that ‘prohibits’ isolated testing. Testing in isolation provides finding bugs easier and bringing code faster under test. Readability, because the Decorator pattern prevents class ‘explosions’. A class explosion might arise when a lot of small variations are required across the inheritance hierarchy. Using inheritance, each variation requires a separate class. The Decorator pattern allows combinations to be made with existing classes (=Decorators). On top of that, the decorator pattern provides separation between ‘core’ (=Concrete component) and decorative logic. In contrast, an inheritance tree intertwines the two.

g.text: The Decorator pattern enables the possibility to extend the behavior of a single object and not the entire class. This can be useful when we don’t want to ‘impact’ all the instances with a new feature. Static inheritance does not provide this possibility.

g.title: Folded Corner.133
g.desc: The Decorator pattern entails both the positive and negative ...

g.text: The Decorator pattern entails both the positive and negative side of the Open Closed Principle. The pattern uses composition to provide extension of the code base without change. Each extension, called a Decorator, has its own class. This might result in a scattered code base that is hard to comprehend and navigate through. Additionally, the pattern allows us to use Decorators around Decorators. Each Decorator follows the Component abstraction. The combination of the two introduces a ‘huge’ form of indirection, which negatively impacts the debuggability and understandability of the code.

g.title: Folded Corner.138
g.desc: The Decorator pattern enables runtime flexibility to attach a...

g.text: The Decorator pattern enables runtime flexibility to attach and detach functionality to an object. The pattern realizes this behavior by specifying so-called Decorator objects. A Decorator object is able to wrap an existing object and enhance its interface. Enhancement means extension of the pre and/or post conditions of the wrapped object. The Decorator complies to the same interface as the wrapped object. This compliance results in runtime flexibility to wrap Decorator around Decorator. Runtime functional enhancement cannot be provided by (static) inheritance. Inheritance forces us to define an extension during compile time.

g.title: Folded Corner.183
g.desc: The Decorator pattern might violate the Liskov Substitution P...

g.text: The Decorator pattern might violate the Liskov Substitution Principle. The post-conditions and/or the pre-conditions of an object are modified by applying the Decorator pattern. This could result in strengthened pre-conditions and weakened post-conditions and thus a violation of Liskov Substitution. A violation of the LSP might result in a higher cyclomatic complexity of the code or potential bugs.

g.title: Folded Corner.189
g.desc: The Decorator pattern can serve as an alternative to sub-clas...

g.text: The Decorator pattern can serve as an alternative to sub-classing. When sub-classing reaches rapid (e.g. exponential) growth, it is often an indication that the issue should be resolved on the object level and not on the static class level. The Decorator resolves this class ‘explosion’ by applying composition and extracting responsibilities in a separate branch of the same class hierarchy. These individual responsibilities can be re-used amongst different Components and simplifies combinations. Another Use Case for the Decorator pattern is when it is not possible to extend via sub-classing nor change, e.g. when the class is marked as ‘final’, sources are not available or we would break existing code.
